`crates/ctx-verify/src` implements the `ctx-verify` binary: a broker that
runs a fixed set of cargo/clippy/script checks and emits one capped, schema-
stable JSON (or terse text) report so verifying a change has bounded,
deterministic cost. Depending on this crate as a library (`lib.rs`
re-exports) gets you `checks::run_selected` plus the `Report`/`CheckReport`/
`Diagnostic` model; depending on it as a binary gets you a process that
exits 0/1/2 for pass/fail/error.

The crate is layered strictly: `runner.rs` is the only place a subprocess is
spawned (`Runner` trait + `ProcRunner`); `checks.rs` is pure orchestration
over that trait (SPECS list, per-check pass/fail/error/skip logic,
`-p <package>` scoping); `parse.rs` turns each tool's raw stdout into
`Diagnostic`s with no I/O; `model.rs` defines the capped/truncated report
shape with hand-written `Serialize` impls; `cli.rs` renders a `Report` to
terse text or JSON; `main.rs`/`error.rs` wire argv, writers, and the shared
`CheckError` taxonomy together. A change to a check's output format touches
two files together: the parser in `parse.rs` and the `Spec`/parser
assignment in `checks.rs`. A change to `Diagnostic` or `CheckReport` fields
in `model.rs` must stay in sync with `parse.rs` (field shape) and with
`cli.rs`'s JSON dump (wire contract for ctx-run/CI) and terse renderer.

Invariants spanning the subtree: every check ends in exactly one of
Pass/Fail/Errored/Skipped, with Errored taking precedence over Fail in
`Report::new`; a check that spawned but produced no diagnostics on failure
always gets a synthesized one-line `Diagnostic` (`checks::failure_hint`);
diagnostics per check are always capped at `max` with overflow recorded in
`truncated`, never silently dropped; only `fmt` mutates the tree (it must
stay first in SPECS), everything else is read-only.